# Machine Learning: Linear Regression

_Example project based on Stefano Bosisio's [Medium article about Machine Learning and Rust](https://levelup.gitconnected.com/machine-learning-and-rust-part-2-linear-regression-d3b820ed28f9)._

Linear Regression is a widely used model in everything from epidemiology to finance and astronomy - usually to estimate some likelihood of certain outcome(s). This type of regression is one among many models in the _Generalized Linear Model_ (GLM) that try to fit a distribution of points. Other models derived from GLM that are also often used in Data Science would be Logistic Regression, Poisson Regression among others.

Fitting, in the case of Linear Regression at least - generally means seeking to find some trend-line among data-points. And since we can derive the formula for that trend-line we can then input our own values instead to get an estimated outcome.

This is illustrated below with a 2-dimensional data-set, but we could easily visualize this line passing through points in a 3-dimensional (or more) chart as well:

![Scatter-plot with trend line](data:image/png;base64,)

The red arrows in the illustration above highlights an important factor impacting GLMs; The variance in the data-set is important as this impacts how well our model would fit - in other words our accuracy; With what certainty will some set of observations `x` end up with some correctly predicted value `y`.

The variance will always be present in real-life applications, and will be some combination of the following:

1. _Consistency of Variance:_ In the final outcome of `y` ( aka our predicted value ) the error against the predicted value should ideally be a constant variance
2. _Approximate Normality of Error:_ The error in the outcome `y` should follow a Normal Distribution
3. _Accumulation of Systematic Effects:_ Depending on the way the calculation is performed, we might have systematic errors during the fitting process. In practice, these might be rounding errors or approximations.

> From the above, we can see that we will always need to make some decision on what data we want to feed the regression algorithm and what accuracy we will require the outcome to have. This is true for Machine Learning in general
